  "opinion": "As a fitness trainer in Bologna with roots in an immigrant family, I've seen how stereotypes can hold people back in every field, including STEM. Stereotype threat isn't just a theory—it's real, tangible anxiety that hits people when they're reminded they're part of a group labeled as less capable in a specific area. For me, it's not about abstract concepts; it's about watching my clients, many of whom come from similar backgrounds to mine, hesitate before they tackle math problems or science experiments because they've internalized the idea that 'I'm not good at this.' This fear, this pressure to prove themselves against a stereotype, can make people disengage entirely. In my experience, addressing it means creating spaces where everyone feels safe to make mistakes without judgment. It's about starting small—like having open conversations in the gym about how learning new skills can be challenging for anyone, not just those who are 'naturally' inclined. When I volunteer with schools, I emphasize that intelligence isn't fixed; it's built through practice and patience. Stereotype threat is a barrier that needs to be dismantled, not ignored. We must address it by fostering environments where people feel valued for who they are, not just what they're expected to do. It's a slow process, but it's worth it. After all, in the gym, we all know that strength comes from showing up, even when you're not sure you can do it.",
